e Revising -- t23 WORKING AT WRITING -- t24 WHEN REVISING A TEXT CAN TRANSFORM YOUR RESEARCH -- t25 REVISIONS AS A COMPLEX INTELLECTUAL JOURNEY -- t26 AUTHOR, EDITOR, AUDIENCE -- t27 WHY I REWRITE -- t28 TO REVISE OR REWRITE ANEW That Is the Question -- t29 THANK YOU, REVIEWER 2 Revising as an Underappreciated Process of Data Analysis -- t30 FIVE FEET AT A TIME -- t31 ABOLISH THE R&R -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABOUT THE AUTHORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout their careers, social scientists must come up with compelling research topics, decide when and where to publish, and revise their manuscripts for publication. Despite the importance of these skills, they are seldom if ever addressed in the course of graduate training. Heavy emphasis is placed on conducting research, and other core activities such as teaching also receive attention, yet fundamental academic practices are left almost entirely in the shadows.Practicing Sociology brings together a range of leading sociologists to reflect on their work and demystify this tacit knowledge. In conversational and engaging essays, they provide practical guidance and hard-won wisdom for readers at any stage of their scholarly careers. The book’s three sections explore the art of finding new research questions, best practices in publishing, and how to make the most out of the peer review process. Contributors’ distinctive voices come through as they recount their frustrations and failures as well as the joys of the sociological craft. They provide a range of perspectives, underscoring that there is no one “right” way to practice sociology but a constellation of different approaches that together give the field its vitality.Practicing Sociology features a team of skilled scholars including Peter Bearman, Paul J. DiMaggio, Wendy Espeland, Marion Fourcade, Shamus Rahman Khan, Eric Klinenberg, Michèle Lamont, Jennifer Lee, Mignon Moore, Mario Small, Duncan Watts, and many more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldassarri, Delia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBearman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckert, Jens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetta, Michela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucchi, Massimiano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarruthers, Bruce G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzarniawska, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimaggio, Paul J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspeland, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFligstein, Neil D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFourcade, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJasper, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, Shamus Rahman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinenberg, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreiner, Kristian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamont, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLury, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, John Levi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc